@article{Antognini2013,
abstract = {Abridged: The Kozai-Lidov (KL) mechanism can accelerate the merger of compact objects via gravitational radiation by driving the inner binaries of hierarchical triples to high eccentricities. We perform direct three-body integrations of a range of high mass ratio ($\sim$100:1) compact object triple systems undergoing KL oscillations using Fewbody and including post-Newtonian terms up to order 3.5. We find that the inner binary undergoes rapid eccentricity oscillations (REOs) on the timescale of the outer orbital period which drive it to higher eccentricities than secular theory would otherwise predict and results in substantially reduced merger times. For a uniform distribution of tertiary eccentricity (e_2), we show that $\sim$40% of systems merge within $\sim$1-2 eccentric KL timescales whereas secular theory predicts that only $\sim$20% of such systems merge that rapidly. The merger time discrepancy between secular theory and the full three-body dynamics becomes especially pronounced at low e_2, with secular theory overpredicting the merger time by many orders of magnitude. We note that $\sim$10% of compact object binaries driven to merger by the eccentric KL mechanism retain non-negligible eccentricity (e > 0.8) when they emit gravitational waves at frequencies detectable by LIGO or LISA for the relevant range of masses, which could have an impact in the residual eccentricity at merger. Our results are applicable to all high mass ratio triple systems containing black holes (of any mass) or neutron stars because our calculations are dimensionless when relativistic corrections are negligible. In physically larger objects in which tidal effects are important, such as white dwarfs, stars, and planets, REOs can reduce the tidal circularization timescale by an order of magnitude and bring the components of the inner binary into closer orbits than would be possible in the secular approximation.},
